\noindent Problem 1. Let $A = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}$.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item The linear transformation $T: \mathbb{R}^2 \to \mathbb{R}^2, T(v) = Av$ is a clockwise rotation of an angle $\theta$: what is $\theta$?
    \item Does $A$ have any real eigenvalues? Justify your answer.
    \item Argue that if $\alpha$ is an eigenvalue for a matrix $B$, then $\alpha^2$ is an eigenvalue for $B^2$.
    \item If we consider only real (not complex) eigenvalues, is it true that if $B^2$ has real eigenvalue $\mu$, then $B$ has real eigenvalue $\alpha = \sqrt{\mu}$? Explain.
\end{enumerate}

