\noindent Problem 2. A 1970 survey determined that 50\% of American car owners drove large cars, 30\% drove middle sized cars and 20\% drove small cars. A second survey in 1980 determined that 40\% of large car owners in 1970, still drove a large car in 1980, but 10\% switched to a middle sized car and 50\% switched to a small car; of the middle sized car owners in 1970, 20\% had switched to a big car, 70\% were still driving a middle sized car, and 10\% were owning a small car; finally, of the small car owners in 1970, 20\% owned a large car in 1980, 20\% owned a middle sized car, and 60\% still owned small cars.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Use a Markov matrix $M$ to describe this situation, that is you want to find a matrix $M$, such that
    \[
    M \begin{pmatrix} 0.5 \\ 0.3 \\ 0.2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \\ c \end{pmatrix}
    \]
    where $a, b, c$ represent the percentages of car owners driving large, medium sized and small cars respectively in 1980.
    \item $\begin{pmatrix} 0.5 \\ 0.7 \\ 0.8 \end{pmatrix}$ is an eigenvector for $M$. What is the eigenvalue associated with it? Explain how you know.
    \item Assuming that every 10 years American switch cars as described above, determine the percentage of Americans that will own large, medium sized and small cars respectively in the long run.
\end{enumerate}

